Wk19 Autoimmunity, food allergy and intolerance; immune induced tissue damage 

Wednesday, August 16, 2017 

11:58 AM 

T cell selection 

Thymocytes (T cells) are 1, positively, then 2, negatively, selected in the thymus. Note that 98% of T cells made in the bone marrow are destroyed in the thymus. This selection process in the thymus is known as central tolerance selection, but mature T cells are still subject to peripheral tolerance processes. 

 

 

After leaving the thymus, T cells can be destroyed by activation-induced cell death (AICD), or their function can be regulated by suppressive cytokines. Also note that privileged immunological sites eg brain, eye, testis, uterus and fetus have active processes which prevent the inflammatory damage of vital organs.  

 

Active mechanisms of peripheral tolerance 

-AICD: repeated stimulation of T cell receptors will eventually cause the attachment of the FasL on an APC to the Fas receptor on the T cell, causing apoptosis. 

-Anergy: reception of MHC II from an APC but without the proper co-stimulus eg reception by CTLA receptor, or through no reception at all, causes functional inactivation of the T cell 

-Suppression: a T regulatory cell (T-reg) can block the activation of a T cell. T-reg cells that recognise self-antigens will inhibit the activation of CD4+ T cells in the lymph nodes that recognise the same self-antigen. 

 

 

However, do note that the sequestration of certain antigens during the embryonic stage can result in certain self-antigens not being considered as self-antigens. Therefore, these antigens can cause an immune response in adulthood if exposed to specific immune cells.  

 

B cell selection 

At the bone marrow, B cells are tested for reaction with self-antigens. If there is no reaction, it moves into the bloodstream. If there is a reaction, it undergoes receptor editing. If all possible sequences are self-reactive, the B cell undergoes apoptosis. If a sequence is found which is non-self-reactive, it is released into the bloodstream. Peripherally, if there is monovalent reception of self-antigens, anergy occurs followed by later cell death. If there is cross-linking of self-antigens, the B cell undergoes apoptosis. 

 

Autoimmunity vs allergy 

Autoimmunity is an exaggeration (hypersensitivity) of a Th1 or Th17 immune response to a self-antigen. 

Allergy is an exaggeration (hypersensitivity type 1 or 4) of a Th2 immune response to an allergen.  

 

The presence of T-reg cells in the GI tract provide peripheral tolerance to minimise the exaggeration of Th1 and Th17 immune responses. Mucosal T-reg cells are activated by antigen exposure.  

 

Define food allergy and food intolerance (or non-allergic hypersensitivity) 

Food allergy occurs when the immune system reacts to a harmless food, whilst food intolerance occurs when the body has a chemical reaction to eating a particular food or drink. Food intolerance does not cause severe allergic reactions such as anaphylaxis. Food intolerance also does not show on allergy testing.  

 

 

Using the examples of lactose intolerance and true milk allergy, compare the mechanisms and manifestations of each 

Lactose intolerance is caused by a lactase deficiency among the brush border enzymes of the small intestine. This results in unabsorbed lactose being present in the intestinal tract. This increases osmotic load due to undigested lactose hence increasing intestinal lumen water and hence diarrhea. Lactose is also fermented by colonic microbes leading to the production of short chain fatty acids and gas (H2, CO2, CH4).  

 

Food allergy is a failure of tolerance. Normally, food antigens reach the intestinal mucosa and enter the GALT areas through M cells. This allows the presentation of the antigen by the dendritic cell to a T cell in a manner causing the T cell to differentiate into a T-reg cell. This keeps the immune response balanced. However if there is a leaky, damaged mucosal barrier, increased antigen uptake occurs, with a bypassing of the normal route through GALT by crossing weakened tight junctions between epithelial cells (immaturity in infants, alcohol ingestion, inflammation of gut tissues). Alternatively, it may result from immaturity or failure of the APC.  

 

Note: milk allergy can be either a Type I (IgE-mediated), Type III or Type IV hypersensitivity.  

 

Infant risk of milk allergy 

-Digestive enzymes not fully active 

-Immature/low secretory IgA allow antigen entry 

-Increased mucosa permeability 

-Undigested proteins reach immune system 

-Reduced gastric acidity and intake of proton pump inhibitors 

  

Note: Unhydrolysed and partially hydrolysed protein in milk contain allergen epitopes, and can generate the allergic response. However, hydrolysed milk destroys allergen epitopes and hence no immune response occurs. Infant formula containing hydrolysed milk proteins can be useful. 

 

Describe the potential mechanisms of tissue damage by the immune system 

Release of proinflammatory cytokines can lead to increased mast cell degranulation to cause tissue damage. Apoptosis-resistance in T cells can also develop, leading to chronic inflammatory bowel disease and hence tissue damage.  

 

Describe the events leading to tissue damage in celiac disease 

In the submucosa, gluten peptides are de-amidated by tissue transglutaminase. The de-amidated gluten has high affinity for binding to HLA-DQ2 and HLA-DQ8 peptides found on APCs. Thus, individuals must carry the HLA-DQ2 or HLA-DQ8 gene to develop Celiac disease.  

 

Celiac disease is a Th1 autoimmune disease, and does not involve IgE or the allergic response. Stressed mucosal epithelial cells release IL15 and interferon, activating APCs to an inflammatory state (viruses and bacteria also activate IL15-activated APCs). The APC presents de-amidated gluten to the mesenteric lymph node (eg Peyer's patch). There, CD4 Th1 cells activate cytotoxic T cells to destroy mucosal epithelial cells. Th2 cells cause Transglutaminase-2 and gluten specific antibodies to be also secreted by plasma B cells.  

 

Note: Celiac disease has both genetic and environmental factors.  

 

Define autoimmunity 

Autoimmunity: a misdirected immune response which results in damage to the body's own cells.
